 {"id": "franken_networkx-isplanarbroken", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] is_planar classified K3,3 and Petersen as planar (both are canonical non-planar graphs)", "description": "fnx's _raw_is_planar Rust binding returned True for K3,3 and the Petersen graph \u2014 two textbook non-planar graphs (K3,3 is one of the two Kuratowski forbidden minors). Critically, fnx's own check_planarity already returned the correct (False, None) for the same inputs, so the two functions publicly contradicted each other. Route is_planar through check_planarity so the answer is consistent and matches nx's reference LR-planarity implementation. Verified on K3/K4/K5/K6/K3,3/C5/petersen/star/wheel.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate to check_planarity for consistency", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-mixmap", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] degree_mixing_matrix / attribute_mixing_matrix default mapping missed inner-only keys AND differed from nx ordering", "description": "When ``mapping=None``, fnx built the default ordering from ``list(mixing)``, i.e. the outer dict's insertion order. This (a) skipped degree/attribute values that only appeared as *neighbor* endpoints (inner-dict keys), silently dropping matrix rows/cols, and (b) left the rows/cols in a different order than nx. Fix: match nx.utils.misc._dict_to_numpy_array2 by taking the set union of outer + inner keys. On a 4-node graph with edges (0,1)(1,2)(2,3)(0,2) fnx used to return [[2,2,0],[2,0,1],[0,1,0]] (ordering [2,3,1]) vs nx's [[0,0,1],[0,2,2],[1,2,0]] (ordering [1,2,3]); now matches nx exactly.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Set-union default mapping", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-degnbnview", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] Graph.degree(nbunch) returned list of tuples; nx returns DegreeView supporting key indexing", "description": "nx.Graph.degree(nbunch) returns a DegreeView-like object that iterates as (node, degree) tuples AND supports ``view[node]`` key lookup. The Rust DegreeView's __call__(list) returned a plain list, so ``G.degree([0,1])[0]`` returned the tuple ``(0, 1)`` rather than the scalar degree. This broke nx.algorithms.bipartite.degrees (which does ``B.degree(top, weight)`` then ``deg[node]``) plus any caller that mixes iteration with key-indexing. Added _FilteredDegreeView proxy class that implements __iter__, __getitem__, __contains__, __len__, and __call__ for weighted + unweighted restricted views. Verified against bipartite.degrees: ``deg[node]`` now returns the scalar and iteration still yields tuples.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T15:45:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Proxy class with DegreeView contract", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-midegcent", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] in_degree_centrality / out_degree_centrality undercounted parallel edges on MultiDiGraph", "description": "The Rust _raw_in_degree_centrality and _raw_out_degree_centrality collapsed parallel multi-edges to a single edge during the degree count on MultiDiGraph input, so every node got in/out-degree=1 after normalization. nx (and fnx's own G.in_degree() / G.out_degree() views) correctly count parallel edges. Added a MultiDiGraph branch that recomputes centrality from G.in_degree()/G.out_degree() scaled by 1/(n-1), matching nx's definition exactly. Verified on a MultiDiGraph with parallel edges and on regular DiGraph (fast-path unchanged).", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Recompute from G.in_degree()/G.out_degree()", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-mgavgnbd", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] average_neighbor_degree wrong on MultiGraph (Rust fast path collapsed parallel edges)", "description": "For MultiGraph with edges (0,1,a),(0,1,b),(1,2,a) nx's formula yields {0:1.5, 1:1.0, 2:3.0} (sum of neighbor degrees over unique neighbors, divided by multi-counted degree). The Rust fast path returned {0:2.0, 1:1.0, 2:2.0} because it built an adjacency view that collapsed parallel edges and also used a collapsed degree count, giving a different ratio. Gate the Rust shortcut on not G.is_multigraph(); the Python fallback already follows nx's contract. Verified on MG and regular Graph.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Skip Rust path for multigraphs", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-nccset", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] node_connected_component returned list; nx returns set", "description": "nx.node_connected_component returns a set of nodes reachable from the query node. The direct re-export of the Rust binding returned a plain list, so callers doing set ops (issubset, intersection, ``x in result`` performance) silently saw wrong behavior or slower O(n) membership. Wrapped the Rust function in a Python wrapper that coerces the list to a set.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Coerce to set", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-chordaltype", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] is_chordal accepted MultiGraph input; nx raises NetworkXNotImplemented", "description": "nx.is_chordal is @not_implemented_for('directed','multigraph') and raises NetworkXNotImplemented. fnx's is_chordal delegated straight to the Rust binding, which accepted a MultiGraph and returned False \u2014 silently giving a wrong answer instead of flagging the unsupported input. Added explicit directed/multigraph checks in the Python wrapper with nx's exact wording.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Python-side type gate", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-mgdegassort", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] degree_assortativity_coefficient returned nan on MultiGraph", "description": "The Rust fast path did not sum parallel-edge contributions when building the degree pair distribution, so the Pearson-style formula hit a zero-variance case and returned nan for any MultiGraph. nx returns a real coefficient (e.g. ~0.1667 on the probe graph). Delegate multigraphs to nx via _call_networkx_for_parity; regular Graph/DiGraph still take the Rust fast path.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T16:00:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Multigraph delegation", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
